      <section>
        <h1>PARC: Contrast</h1>
        <p>Contrast is the idea of using different tools, including font, color and size, in order to draw the viewers attention to important details.</p>
        <p>As seen below, <a href="http://facebook.com"> Facebook </a> does an excellet job at using color contrast to draw attention to details they want the user to view. Such as using a completely different color, for the "create an account" button, and a lighter blue to log in.
        </p>
        <img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55597694/65791416-eba15c80-e11e-11e9-8e89-8c063adb6a70.JPG" alt="Facebook Mobile">
        <div class="website-link">
        <a href="http://facebook.com">https://www.Facebook.com</a>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h1>PARC: Alignment</h1>
        <p>Alignment is the principle that in order to keep the viewers attention, images, text and and other element on a web page, should be neatly organized. Establishing elements on clean lines gives off a better feeling of organization and professionalism.</p>
        <p> The <a href="http://nytimes.com"> New York Times</a> website achieves this by establishing all their bullet points points, and healine, on the same vertical line.</p>
        <img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55597694/65792523-2a381680-e121-11e9-9269-72b5be507a6e.JPG" alt="New York Times">
        <div class="website-link">
          <a href="http://Nytimes.com">https://www.nytimes.com</a>
        </div>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h1>PARC: Proximity</h1>
        <p>The principle of proximity is what helps us understand the spacing and relationship between different elements on a web page. Items put together should be similar, while items that are different should be spaced out. </p>
        <p> <a href="http://Amazon.com">Amazon</a> does this by putting their navigation options grouped together on the top of their webpage, while putting deals and items at the bottom of the page. </p>
        <img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55597694/65793786-e397eb80-e123-11e9-9a24-0957a267c8bf.JPG" alt="Amazon mobile">
        <div class="website-link">
        <a href="http://Amazon.com">https://www.Amazon.com</a>
        </div>
